 challenging and provocative new account of what pictures are and how they function.The book demonstrates these ideas with a series of compelling case studies, ranging from Dante's picture theory to post-photography. One chapter explores the tension between image and medium in two "media of the body," the coat of arms and the portrait painting. Another, central chapter looks at the relationship between image and death, tracing picture production, including the first use of the mask, to early funerary rituals in which pictures served to represent the missing bodies of the dead. Pictures were tools to re-embody the deceased, to make them present again, a fact that offers a surprising clue to the riddle of presence and absence in most pictures and that reveals a genealogy of pictures obscured by Platonic picture theory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aEthnology in art. 0aVisual anthropology. 0aVisual sociology. 7aART / Criticism.2bisacsh  aAlex Katz.  aAllegory.  aAnalogy.  aAnecdote.  aAnthropology of art.  aAnthropology of media.  aAntithesis.  aAphorism.  aArchaeology.  aArt criticism.  aArt history.  aArt.  aBody image.  aCamera Work.  aCamera.  aCase study.  aClose-up.  aCoat of arms.  aConceptual art.  aConsciousness.  aCountermovement.  aCreation myth.  aCreative work.  aCultural anthropology.  aCultural geography.  aCultural heritage.  aCultural history.  aCultural memory.  aDichotomy.  aEmblem.  aEmerging technologies.  aEscutcheon (heraldry).  aExplanation.  aFilm theory.  aFine art.  aFunerary art.  aGenre.  aGeorges Bataille.  aGudea.  aHistorical anthropology.  aHistoricity.  aHistoriography.  aHuman figure (aesthetics).  aHumanism.  aHumanities.  aIconicity.  aIconoclasm.  aIconography.  aIconology.  aIl